    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1940-06-15T07:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1940-06-15T07:00:00-05:00" n="391"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d391">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">500.C/1015: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Consul General at Geneva</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Tittmann</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Geneva</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1940-06-15T13:00:00+01:00"
                            >June 15, 1940—1 p.m.</date>
                        <lb/> [Received 4:30 p.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>91. The Secretary General of the League of Nations has received a joint telegram
                    dated June 12 [<hi rend="italic">11</hi>] from President Dodds of Princeton
                    University, Carl TenBroeck, Director of the Rockefeller Institute for Medical
                    Research, and Frank Aydelotte, Director of the Institute of Advanced Study,
                    inviting the Secretary General to transfer the technical sections of the League
                    to Princeton and offering facilities for continuing the work there.<note n="15"
                        xml:id="d391fn15">
                        <hi rend="italic">Documents on American Foreign Relations</hi>, vol. <hi
                            rend="smallcaps">iii</hi>, July 1940–June 1941, p. 640.</note>
                </p>
                <p>Avenol is replying direct to this telegram and is declining.<note n="16"
                        xml:id="d391fn16">
                        <hi rend="italic">Ibid.</hi>, p. 642.</note> He has asked me to inform the
                    Department of the foregoing and to state that for a number of reasons he feels
                    that he should not accept the invitation under the present circumstances. He
                    added, moreover, that <pb facs="0327" n="318" xml:id="pg_318"/> at no time and
                    under no circumstances would he consider such an invitation without prior
                    understanding with our Government.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Tittmann</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
